Anonymous Wed 27 Jul 2022 02:14:12 No.49646962 Report
Quoted By: >>49647038 >>49647047 >>49647207 >>49647519
>>49646449
I'm of differing thoughts on this.
I used to be able to habitually write, and usually had to rely on this when I was struggling with downer phases of my mood (to the point I feel like everything I'm creating is absolute trite bullshit). What I found was that while at the time I hated what I'd written, and a bunch of it needed heavier tweaking than normal, I'd always make *something* worthwhile in there.
But on the other hand, I spent four months writing a full novel-length thing on a whim a while ago, enjoyed myself immensely, had almost endless energy creating it, yet when it was posted (in a whole other community and psuedonym) it didn't exactly make waves. It had a following, sure. It also happened to be one of the few pieces I liked going back to reading for my own pleasure.
I almost never do that. I'll reread a thing for proof-reading and editing, obviously, and I'll generally give it a final run for triple-checking, and I'll reread parts later to make sure I reference things properly, but for my own enjoyment? That's rare.

I suppose I can make that a follow-on question for other writefags; do you generally enjoy reading your own stuff? Or do you normally have it so deeply ingrained in your psyche that you don't find it necessary and/or enjoyable?

In other news; a story I don't know anyone asked for a continuance for is getting just that 'soon'. Still a chapter and an act ender to finish, and two chapters and said ender to be proofed. Probably still gonna be a couple of weeks. Currently looking at 45,000 words.
